bug.short_desc: -clean required after Eclipse SDK upgrade (Linux distribution)

long_desc.thetext:
This is a weird problem so please indulge this weird bug report :) . I apologize if this is the wrong product/component.
In Fedora, we ship the Eclipse SDK. The jars are placed in /usr/share/eclipse (unwritable as a regular user) and the fragments are place in /usr/lib/eclipse. Stuff is therefore written to ~/.eclipse.
If a user has version 3.3.0 of the SDK and upgrades to 3.3.1.1 (upgrades their RPMs, that is), they get odd behaviour (ClassCastExceptions opening java editors, for one) on their next startup. If the user runs with -clean, they don't have any problems. Any suggestions about where to look to figure out what is going wrong here and/or what I can do to fix it are greatly appreciated.

(In reply to comment #0) > In Fedora, we ship the Eclipse SDK. The jars are placed in /usr/share/eclipse > (unwritable as a regular user) and the fragments are place in /usr/lib/eclipse. > Stuff is therefore written to ~/.eclipse.
I assume /usr/lib/eclipse is unwritable as a regular user also? Also why is there a distinction between the jars and the fragments? Is there a default configuration directory (where the config.ini is located)? Is that in /usr/share/eclipse or /usr/lib/eclipse? Does the configuration folder located in the unwritable area contain any cached information? Or is the chached data only located somewhere in ~/.eclipse?
> > If a user has version 3.3.0 of the SDK and upgrades to 3.3.1.1 (upgrades their > RPMs, that is), they get odd behaviour (ClassCastExceptions opening java > editors, for one) on their next startup. If the user runs with -clean, they > don't have any problems. Any suggestions about where to look to figure out > what is going wrong here and/or what I can do to fix it are greatly > appreciated. >
Does the RPM upgrade replace any of the jars? Or is it simply laying down the new versions of the bundles and fragments? Can you elaborate on how RPM does the upgrade to 3.3.1.1? Does it use Eclipse Update or is it simply overlaying the 3.3.1.1 content over 3.3.0?

I've had some similar experiences using an Eclipse-based product on Windows XP. I'd install WST through the 'Update Manager' and then tell it to restart and all sorts of views will fail to load (such as the 'Navigator'). Restarting by hand with -clean fixed the problem though. So I started to install plug-ins through the 'Update Manager' but restart Eclipse with -clean manually (instead of having it reboot for me).

I didn't want to make this too long so I kept responses terse. I can elaborate and provide directory listings as required.
(In reply to comment #1) > (In reply to comment #0) > > In Fedora, we ship the Eclipse SDK. The jars are placed in /usr/share/eclipse > > (unwritable as a regular user) and the fragments are place in > /usr/lib/eclipse. > > Stuff is therefore written to ~/.eclipse. > > I assume /usr/lib/eclipse is unwritable as a regular user also?
Yes,
> Also why is there a distinction between the jars and the fragments?
The arch-specific stuff (fragments) goes in the arch-specific directory (/usr/lib or /usr/lib64)/eclipse and the arch-independent bytecode goes into /usr/share/eclipse.
> Is there a default configuration directory (where the config.ini is located)?
Yes, /usr/lib/eclipse/configuration.
> Does the configuration folder located > in the unwritable area contain any cached information?
Yes, it contains what the Equinox FileInitializer (I believe the incubator jar is org.eclipse.equinox.initializer) application outputs with an input of *.so -> .sos nested in jars.
> Or is the chached data > only located somewhere in ~/.eclipse?
There is stuff in here, too.
> > If a user has version 3.3.0 of the SDK and upgrades to 3.3.1.1 (upgrades their > > RPMs, that is), they get odd behaviour (ClassCastExceptions opening java > > editors, for one) on their next startup. If the user runs with -clean, they > > don't have any problems. Any suggestions about where to look to figure out > > what is going wrong here and/or what I can do to fix it are greatly > > appreciated. > > > > Does the RPM upgrade replace any of the jars?
Yes, the old contents are removed and the new ones are laid down.
> Can you elaborate on how RPM does > the upgrade to 3.3.1.1?
It's simply over-laying the bundles and .xml files. A straight file-level swap.

(In reply to comment #4) > Hi Andrew, sorry for the delay on this bug. Do you happen to have the error > log with the classloading errors? Did the error indicate that > org.eclipse.core.databinding could not be activated?
Hi Tom,
Don't worry about the delay. I have the packages of the two versions on my laptop and was planning on showing you at EclipseCon.
In the meantime, I'll reproduce and post the error here.
Thanks.

I started with 3.3.0 and created a Mylyn task and a Java class. I left the task active and the editor open. When I restarted, I got a bunch of errors. I'll attach a screenshot and the traces in the editor and mylyn view. Should I attach anything else?
I had installed a lot of Ganymede using the update manager (to prove to someone else that it worked :) so my /home/overholt/.eclipse was already quite large. But here are the sizes before and after the upgrade (the second one being after I'd started 3.3.1.1):
$ du -s .eclipse.{3.3.0,afterupgrade} 143944 .eclipse.3.3.0 143580 .eclipse.afterupgrade
Created attachment 91233 workbench after upgrade
Created attachment 91234 editor trace (copied after pressing Details)
Created attachment 91235 view trace (copied after pressing Details)
Does your errorlog have any more details? In your original description you mentioned cast exceptions but these errors only show NPEs.

(In reply to comment #10) > Does your errorlog have any more details? In your original description you > mentioned cast exceptions but these errors only show NPEs.
I originally got cast exceptions in the editor similar to the NPEs I attached. Now it appears I'm only getting NPEs. I can repeat the procedure and/or attach other stuff if necessary.

Andrew and I tried to debug this at EclipseCon (and in frustration I almost spilled beer all over our laptops!!)
We were not able confirm this, but I suspect that we have some bundles that have optional dependencies that are not get satisfied on an the update. This is related to bug 176872 (fixed in p2). Basically p2 (simple.configurator) will detect bundles with optional dependencies that are not satisfied but there is a valid supplier available for the dependency. These bundles are forced to refresh.
Andrew was going to do some additional investigation to find all the optional dependencies in his environment and determine if they are not satisfied. Andrew, did you make any progress here?

(In reply to comment #12) > Andrew was going to do some additional investigation to find all the optional > dependencies in his environment and determine if they are not satisfied. > Andrew, did you make any progress here?
I'm sorry but I didn't get a chance to do this yet. I was planning on doing it on Monday.

Tom:
For optional dependencies, you mean bundles with entries like this in their MANIFEST.MF, right?
Require-Bundle: org.eclipse.ant.core;bundle-version="[3.1.0,4.0.0)";resolution:=optional,
I can reliably get the error with a small workspace I have. I tried starting eclipse with -console and typing "refresh org.eclipse.jdt.ui" and it gave all sorts of other errors and requested a perspective reload. I tried that but it didn't work.
Is the command of "refresh <bundle id>" what I should be doing? Should I just keep trying this with each of the bundles that have resolution:=optional?

Hi Andrew,
I recommend you start with the following options
eclipse -console -noexit -vmargs -Declipse.application.launchDefault=false
This should get you an osgi> prompt without actually starting the application. From here you can perform all the refresh operations you want without having to worry about effecting the running instance of eclipse.
Any bundle that has a Require-Bundle or Import-Package manifest header with resolution:=optional has an optional constraint. I would like you to refresh all of these types of bundles. Then run "close" to shutdown. Then restart eclipse normally.

Hi Tom,
Thanks for the instructions. I followed them like this:
$ cat /usr/lib/eclipse/eclipse.ini.orig -showsplash org.eclipse.platform -vmargs -Xms40m -Xmx256m -XX:MaxPermSize=128m
$ eclipse
Notice errors like java editor throws error dialog stating "Error opening the editor \n null argument" and the editor itself has weird tabs and a stack trace in it -- the same as the previously attached "editor trace", attachment #91234.
$ cat /usr/lib/eclipse/eclipse.ini.fordebugging -showsplash org.eclipse.platform -console -noexit -vmargs -Declipse.application.launchDefault=false -Xms40m -Xmx256m -XX:MaxPermSize=128m
$ sudo cp /usr/lib/eclipse/eclipse.ini{.fordebugging,} $ eclipse
osgi> refresh org.eclipse.ant.ui osgi> refresh org.eclipse.core.databinding osgi> refresh org.eclipse.core.filebuffers osgi> refresh org.eclipse.core.resources osgi> refresh org.eclipse.core.runtime osgi> refresh org.eclipse.equinox.app osgi> refresh org.eclipse.equinox.preferences osgi> refresh org.eclipse.equinox.registry osgi> refresh org.eclipse.help.base osgi> refresh org.eclipse.jdt.core osgi> refresh org.eclipse.osgi.services osgi> refresh org.eclipse.pde.build osgi> refresh org.eclipse.pde.junit.runtime osgi> refresh org.eclipse.pde.runtime osgi> refresh org.eclipse.platform osgi> refresh org.eclipse.team.cvs.ui osgi> refresh org.eclipse.team.ui osgi> refresh org.eclipse.tomcat osgi> refresh org.eclipse.ui.cheatsheets osgi> refresh org.eclipse.ui.externaltools osgi> refresh org.eclipse.ui.forms osgi> refresh org.eclipse.ui.intro osgi> close
$ sudo cp /usr/lib/eclipse/eclipse.ini{.orig,} $ eclipse
Now I get no errors in the workbench and things appear normal. Sweet!

(In reply to comment #16) > Now I get no errors in the workbench and things appear normal. Sweet! >
OK, this should confirm that we have an optional constraint (that likely really isn't optional) that is not wired and is causing us issues. This has been addressed in p2 (bug 176872) which forces bundles with optional constraints not satisfied to be refreshed. A similar fix could be done to update.configurator that was done to simpleconfigurator to fix this. Moving to update. Andrew, this is still blocking you? Do you have any acceptable work around?

(In reply to comment #17) > Andrew, this is still blocking you? Do you have any acceptable work around?
It's blocking in the sense that I can't upgrade from 3.3.0 which is in Fedora 8. It also means that users upgrading from Fedora 8 to Fedora 9 (which has 3.3.2) will have these issues upon first startup in their newly-upgraded system.
The only workaround I can think of is to tell users to run with -clean (easier than telling them the above steps ;). I guess I could put -clean into the eclipse.ini that we ship. But then I'd have to leave it there and I don't really want to penalize startup like that. Is there something better I can do?

The Eclipse Update component is no longer under development, and no longer exists in the Eclipse Platform 4.x stream. If this problem still occurs in Eclipse Platform 4.2 or later, please enter a new bug report against Equinox p2.
